What does the man command do? Type in man rm. How do you scroll and get out?
- The man command opens the manual for any given command you want to know more about. up and down arrow, q to close the manual.

Look at the man page for ls. What does the -l flag do? What does the -a flag do?
-l uses a long listing format. -a (all) do not ignore entries starting with.

How do you jump between words in the terminal?
alt + left/right arrow

How do you get to the end of a line in terminal?
control  + e
How do you move your cursor to the beginning in terminal?
control + a
How do you delete a word (without pressing backspace multiple times) in terminal?
control + w

What is the difference between a terminal and shell?
The terminal is the overall system reader that runs the Shells (programs).

 What is an absolute path? 
 the absolute path is every step it takes to get to the file of choice. e.g: /c/Users/Micah/Desktop/example.txt
 
What is an relative path?
describes the location of a file relative to the current (working) directory

What is a flag? Give three examples of flags you have used.
flags are used to better specify commands. e.g: -l lists items one line per item. -a lists all the items in a directory. -r removes directories and there content

What do the r and f flags do with the rm command?
-r removes directories and there content and -f (force) ignore nonexistent files and arguments, never prompt
